{{Nihongo|'''Burikko'''|ぶりっ子||sometimes rendered '''Burriko''' in English}} is a Japanese term for a style of personal appearance and demeanor that is considered childish and cute, sometimes excessively so. The term was [[neologism|coined]] during the 1980s, and is sometimes attributed to Japanese comedian [[Kuniko Yamada]],<ref>{{cite book|year=1987|last=Cherry|first=Kittredge|title=Womansword: What Japanese Words Say about Women|isbn=9780870117947}}</ref> though its exact moment of invention is unclear. Burikko style is often associated with [[Japanese idol]]s of the 1980s such as [[Seiko Matsuda]].<ref>{{cite book|year=2004|first=Laura|last=Miller|chapter=You are Doing Burikko!|title=Japanese Language, Gender, and Ideology|isbn=9780195166170|editors=Shigeko Okamoto and Janet Shibamoto Smith}}</ref> It is associated with the Japanese notion of ''[[kawaii]]'', meaning "cute", which has become important in modern [[Japanese culture]]. 

Burikko is being cute, but with a childlike style to go along with it. It includes the "idea of a helpless, submissive, and cute look of a young girl".<ref>{{cite web|date=May 3, 2005|last=Read|first=Jeremy|title=Kawaii: Culture of cuteness|work=Japan Reference|url=http://www.jref.com/culture-society/kawaii-cuteness/ |accessdate=2018-10-04}}</ref> Behaviors associated with burikko include "kitten writing", a rounded form of handwriting characters, as well as forms of baby talk "to sound like children learning to speak".<ref>{{cite web|date=April 30, 2014|title=Tag Archives: kawaii culture|work=Kawaii Study Japan|url=http://www.kawaiistudyjapan.com/?tag%3Dkawaii-culture |accessdate=2014-11-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129023647/http://www.kawaiistudyjapan.com/?tag=kawaii-culture |archivedate=2014-11-29 |df= }}</ref> As part of this childish way of speaking, people may refer to themselves by name as though they are talking about a third person.

