'''Turko-Iranian''' describes several cultural aspects of Iran, involving various combinations of Turkic and Iranian (or Persian) elements. * The various [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] and [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] hybrid traits pertaining to [[culture]], dynasties as well [[population genetics]] of various peoples in [[Central Asia]], as well as parts of [[Southwest Asia]] and [[South Asia]]. (''See also'': [[Persianate]], [[Turko-Persian Tradition]].) * The [[Oghuz languages|Oghuz]] and [[Iranian Languages|Iranian]] speaking countries such as [[Azerbaijan]], [[Turkmenistan]], and [[Uzbekistan]] whose cultures have been influenced by the [[Persianate society]] and who are a part of the [[Greater Iran]].<ref>Sh.J. Boss, on the ''[[Encyclopaedia Iranica]]'': "Comprehensive research project about the ''Iranian Cultural Continent'' thrives on Riverside Drive", [[Columbia College of Columbia University|''Columbia College Today'']], ([http://www.college.columbia.edu/cct/nov03/features5.php LINK] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060509130141/http://www.college.columbia.edu/cct/nov03/features5.php |date=2006-05-09 }})</ref> * The [[Turkic languages|Turkic]] speaking minorities of [[Iran]]—e.g., [[Azeris]], [[Qashqai people|Qashqais]]. (See [[Iranian Turks]]) * [[Turco-Persian]] society in the 15th to 17th centuries. * A term for those living on the [[Iran]]–[[Turkey]] border. * A term used to refer to the bilateral relations between [[Turkey-Iran relations|Turkey and Iran]].
